  <article xml:id="article">
    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="worksheet">
      <title>Worksheet for Sections 5.1–5.4</title>

      <introduction>
        <p>
          These exercises are designed to help you practice the concepts of the definite integral and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            The rate at which the world’s oil is being consumed is increasing.
            Suppose that the rate (measured in billions of barrels per year) is given by the function <m>r(t)</m>, where <m>t</m> is measured in years and <m>t = 0</m> on January 1, 1990.
          </p>
        </introduction>


        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Write a definite integral that represents the total quantity of oil used between the start of 1990 and the start of 1995.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              <m>\int_0^5 r(t)\,dt</m>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>


        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Suppose that <m>r(t) = 32 e^{0.05 t}</m>.
              Find the approximate value for the definite integral from part (a) using a right-hand sum with <m>n = 5</m> subintervals.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Since the interval is <m>5</m> wide, <m>\Delta t = 1</m>.
              So
              <me>
                \begin{aligned} \int_0^5 r(t)\,dt \approx R_5 &amp;= 32e^{0.05 \cdot 1} + 32e^{0.05 \cdot 2} + 32e^{0.05 \cdot 3} + 32e^{0.05 \cdot 4} + 32e^{0.05 \cdot 5}  \\ &amp;\approx 186.3585.
                \end{aligned}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>


        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Interpret each of the five terms in the sum from part (b) in terms of oil consumption.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Each of the five terms is the rate of oil consumption at the end of the <m>i</m>th year.
              It approximates the amount of oil consumed over the entire year.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>


        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Evaluate the definite integral from part (a) exactly using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              <me>
                \begin{aligned} \int_0^5 r(t)\,dt &amp;= \int_0^5 32 e^{0.05t}\,dt  \\ &amp;= \left.\frac{32}{0.05} e^{0.05t} \right|^5_0 \\ &amp;=  \left(e^{0.25} -1\right) \\ &amp;\approx 181.776 \end{aligned}
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </exercise>

      <exercise workspace="2in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which of the following are equal to
            <me>
              \int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx
            </me>
            ?
          </p>
        </statement>


        <choices>
          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\sum_{i = 1}^5 \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                This is <m>R_5</m> approximating <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx</m>
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{i = 1}^5 \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                The sum counts only the first five terms in <m>R_n</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{i = 1}^n \frac{\ln x_i}{x_i} \Delta x</m>, where <m>\Delta x = 4/n</m> and <m>x_i = 1 + i \Delta x_i</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                Yes, this is <m>\lim_{n\to\infty} R_n</m>, which converges to <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="yes">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(\ln 5)^2/2</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                Yes.
                <m>\frac{d}{dx}\frac{1}{2}\left(\ln x\right)^2 = \ln(x) \cdot \frac{1}{x}</m>, so
                <me>
                  \begin{aligned} \int_1^5 \int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx &amp;= \left.\frac{1}{2}\left(\ln x\right)^2\right|^5_1 \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 5\right)^2 - \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 1\right)^2 \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\left(\ln 5\right)^2 \end{aligned}
                </me>
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{5^2} - \frac{1}{1^2}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                No, this is not correct.
                You may be using <m>\frac{1}{x^2}</m> as an antiderivative of <m>\frac{\ln x}{x}</m>, which it is not.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>

          <choice correct="no">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \frac{\ln 1}{1} + \frac{\ln 2}{2} + \frac{\ln 3}{3} + \frac{\ln 4}{4}</m>
              </p>
            </statement>

            <feedback>
              <p>
                No, this is not correct.
                This is the sum of the first four terms in <m> R_n</m>, which approximates <m>\int_1^5 \frac{\ln x}{x} \, dx</m>.
                The correct answer is the limit of <m>R_n</m> as <m>n\to\infty</m>.
              </p>
            </feedback>
          </choice>
        </choices>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Put the following in <term>ascending</term> order (with <q> <m>=</m> </q> or <q> <m>&lt;</m> </q> signs between each expression.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <hint>
          <p>
            Think about which expressions are positive, which are negative, and which are zero.
            A picture may be helpful.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <blocks> <block>
        <p>
          <m>\ln(2/6)</m>
        </p>
        </block> <block>

        <p>
          <m>0</m>
        </p>
        </block> <block>

        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\ln(2 + h) - \ln 2}{h}</m>
        </p>
        </block> <block>

        <p>
          <m>\ln 2 + \ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 5</m>
        </p>
        </block> <block>

        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \int_2^6 \ln t \, dt</m>
        </p>
        </block> <block>

        <p>
          <m>\ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 5 + \ln 6</m>
        </p>
        </block> </blocks>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  We have <m>\ln(2/6)  = \ln(1/3) = - \ln 3 &lt; 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\ln(2 + h) - \ln 2}{h}</m> is the derivative of <m>\ln x</m> at <m>x = 2</m>, which is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, so it is greater than zero.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Since <m>e &lt; 4</m>, we have <m> \sqrt{e} &lt; 2</m>, so <m>\ln 2 &gt; \ln \sqrt{e} = \frac{1}{2}</m>.
                  Since <m> \ln 3 &gt; \ln 2</m>, and all the other logarithms are positive, we know that both sums of logarithms are greater than <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The sum <m>\ln 2 + \ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 5</m> is an approximation to the integral <m>\int_2^6 \ln t \, dt</m> using a left-hand sum with four subintervals, so it is less than the integral.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The sum <m>\ln 3 + \ln 3 + \ln 4 + \ln 6</m> is an approximation to the integral <m>\int_2^6 \ln t \, dt</m> using a right-hand sum with four subintervals, so it is less than the integral.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
